<HEADLINE>
<P>
TRAFFIC OFFICIALS SEEK TO BAN SKATERS FROM SEPULVEDA BASIN BRIDGES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles traffic officials want to put the brakes on roller skaters and 
skateboarders who use two bridges in the Sepulveda Dam Recreation Area. 
</P>
<P>
City transportation officials have concluded that the two bridges, though safe 
for bicyclists and joggers, are unsafe for roller skaters and skateboarders, 
and have urged the City Council to prohibit such use. 
</P>
<P>
In response, the council's Transportation and Traffic Committee recommended 
Thursday that the council give the Department of Transportation authority to 
regulate bicycling, roller-skating and skateboarding when it considers such 
uses to be unsafe. 
</P>
<P>
The bridges over the Los Angeles River -- one on Balboa Boulevard and the other 
on Burbank Boulevard -- contain metal plates designed to slide as the bridges 
expand and contract because of temperature changes, according to a Department 
of Transportation report to the committee. 
</P>
<P>
Transportation officials were unaware of any serious injuries to roller skaters 
or skateboarders on the bridges. 
</P>
<P>
Though barred from riding across the bridge, roller skaters and skateboarders 
can use the sidewalk in the rest of the basin, officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Los Angeles officials say metal plate, left, and sidewalk on Balboa 
Boulevard bridge threaten skateboarders and roller skaters. BORIS YARO / Los 
Angeles Times 
</P>
