<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The narrowest measure of the nation's money supply, M1, rose $6.7 billion to a 
seasonally adjusted $793.1 billion from $786.4 billion in the week ended Jan. 
2, the Federal Reserve Board reported. Its growth in 1988 was 4.3%. A broader 
measure, M2, rose $3.1 billion to a seasonally adjusted $3,068.7 billion, from 
$3,065.6 billion the week before. M2 grew 5.4% in 1988, according to a 
comparison of the last 13 weeks of 1988 with the last 13 weeks of 1987. M1 
includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts and non-bank 
travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings deposits and money market 
mutual funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
