<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ogilvy Group has adopted a "poison pill" anti-takeover plan, which would make a 
takeover prohibitively expensive. The move caused shares of Ogilvy, the 
sixth-largest U.S. advertising agency, to drop $1.25 to $31.25 on the NASDAQ 
market after it announced that its board passed the plan at a special meeting. 
Ogilvy stock had risen sharply in recent days on takeover talk. But the New 
York company, whose main subsidiary is Ogilvy &amp; Mather Worldwide, said it 
knew of no suitors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
