<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALMANAC / COUNTY'S HOTELS AND MOTELS: OCCUPANCY DROPS BUT PRICES DON'T 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The room occupancy rate at Orange County's hotels and motels dropped to 70.7% 
from 71.9% in the 10 months ending in October, 1987 compared to the 
year-earlier period, according to Pannell Kerr Forster, an accounting and hotel 
consulting firm. The average daily room rate rose to $69.90 from $68.46. 
</P>
<P>
The airport-Newport Beach area was the only one of four county areas that 
registered an increase in occupancy. The tourist-rich Anaheim area showed a 2% 
drop, but it still had the highest occupancy rate, 75.5%. 
</P>
<P>
Hotel rooms in the county are a relative bargain compared to other California 
cities. A separate survey of average room rates in the first 9 months of last 
year showed that San Francisco, San Diego and Los Angeles all were more 
expensive to stay in than Orange County. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
COMPARING AREAS IN STATE 
</P>
<P>
Average daily room rate for 9 months ended Sept. 30, 1988 
</P>
<P>
Orange County: $69.61 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles: 72.07 
</P>
<P>
San Diego: 77.22 
</P>
<P>
San Francisco: 86.41 
</P>
<P>
</P>
